        <TableRow>
          <TableCell>
            <Paragraph FontSize="22"><Run>How to: Get the Binding Object from a Bound Target Property</Run>

            </Paragraph>

          </TableCell>

        </TableRow>

      </TableRowGroup>

    </Table>

    <Paragraph>This example shows how to obtain the binding object from a bound target property.
    </Paragraph>

    <Paragraph FontSize="22">Example
    </Paragraph>

    <Paragraph>To get the Binding object, you need to get the BindingExpression for a specified bound property on a <Run>binding target</Run>
 object and then use the ParentBinding property, as in the following example:
    </Paragraph>

    <Table CellSpacing="5">
      <TableRowGroup>
        <TableRow>
          <TableCell>
            <Paragraph FontSize="22"><Run>C# </Run>

            </Paragraph>

          </TableCell>

        </TableRow>

        <TableRow>
          <TableCell>
            <Paragraph xml:space="preserve" TextAlignment="Left" FontSize="8pt" FontFamily="Courier New"><Run>BindingExpression myBindingExpression = textBox3.GetBindingExpression(TextBox.TextProperty); 
Binding myBinding = myBindingExpression.ParentBinding; 
</Run>

            </Paragraph>

          </TableCell>

        </TableRow>

      </TableRowGroup>

    </Table>

    <Table CellSpacing="5">
      <TableRowGroup>
        <TableRow>
          <TableCell>
            <Paragraph>Note: 
            </Paragraph>

          </TableCell>

        </TableRow>

        <TableRow>
          <TableCell>
            <Paragraph>You must specify the <Run>dependency property</Run>
 for the binding you want because it is possible that more than one property of the target object is using data binding, and the different bindings may not be using the same data context.
            </Paragraph>

          </TableCell>

        </TableRow>

      </TableRowGroup>

    </Table>

    <Paragraph>Alternatively, you can use the GetBinding method of the BindingOperations class.
    </Paragraph>

    <Paragraph>For the complete example see Binding Validation Sample.
    </Paragraph>

